  "@type": "Article",
  "dateModified": "2026-03-06",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "A legal fiction is a statement accepted as true by a legal system despite being known to be false or at least unverifiable — adopted not because it describes reality but because it produces useful legal results. Corporate personhood is the paradigmatic example: the law treats a corporation as a \u0026ldquo;person\u0026rdquo; who can own property, enter contracts, sue and be sued. No one believes a corporation is literally a person. The fiction exists because it solves a practical problem — how to assign rights and obligations to collective entities.\n",
